  <h2 id="ag-structure">The AG Structure at a Glance</h2>
  <p>The Aktiengesellschaft (AG) is the most common corporate form for larger businesses in Switzerland. It offers limited liability to shareholders and is well-suited for companies seeking to raise capital or establish a strong corporate presence.</p>
  <p>Key features of the AG include a minimum share capital requirement of CHF 100,000, a board of directors responsible for strategic oversight, and the ability to issue bearer or registered shares.</p>

  <h2 id="core-requirements">Core Requirements for Incorporation</h2>
  <p>To form a Swiss AG, the following requirements must be met:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Minimum share capital of CHF 100,000 (at least 50% paid in)</li>
    <li>At least one shareholder (individual or legal entity)</li>
    <li>At least one director who is a Swiss resident</li>
    <li>A registered office address in Switzerland</li>
    <li>Articles of association notarised by a Swiss notary</li>
    <li>A Stampa Declaration confirming no undisclosed assets exist</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="formation-process">The Formation Process: Step-by-Step</h2>
  <p>The formation of a Swiss AG follows a structured process that typically involves several key stages:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Name verification</strong> — Check availability of the proposed company name with the commercial register.</li>
    <li><strong>Draft articles of association</strong> — Prepare the constitutional documents defining the company's purpose, capital structure, and governance.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital deposit</strong> — Open a capital deposit account at a Swiss bank and transfer the required share capital.</li>
    <li><strong>Notarial deed</strong> — Execute the formation deed before a Swiss notary public.</li>
    <li><strong>Commercial register entry</strong> — File the application with the cantonal commercial register office.</li>
    <li><strong>Tax and VAT registration</strong> — Register with the relevant tax authorities and, if applicable, for VAT.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2 id="timeline">Timeline and Delays</h2>
  <p>Under normal circumstances, the formation process takes between 2 and 4 weeks. However, certain factors can cause delays:</p>
  <p>Bank account opening may require additional time due to enhanced due diligence procedures, particularly for foreign shareholders. Complex corporate structures with multiple layers of ownership may also extend the timeline.</p>

  <h2 id="why-zug">Why Choose Zug?</h2>
  <p>The Canton of Zug has become one of the most popular locations for company formation in Switzerland due to its business-friendly environment and competitive tax rates.</p>
  <p>With an effective corporate tax rate of approximately 11.85%, Zug offers significant advantages compared to other Swiss cantons. The canton also benefits from a streamlined registration process and proximity to Zurich's financial centre.</p>

